Introduction

In this tutorial, we want to explore potential relationships between various housing market factors in San Francisco. In order to do so, we will analyze building permit data in San Francisco between 2013 and 2018. We aim to explore questions such as, "Are there any factors that affect building permit completion?" and "Are certain permit types commonly issued at similar times?".

San Francisco and the state of California are in the midst of one of the most acute housing crises in the country, and the city is notorious globally for its very slow increases in year-over-year housing supply; some estimates suggest at the current rate of housing permit approvals, it would take the city decades to meet the shortage of housing units today.

This tutorial will guide you through a dataset of the city's building permits to develop a model that will predict the likelihood of a permit approvalas well as to learn how different factors relate to the status of a permit. These permits include more than just housing construction, but they can provide insight into how the city approaches permits, and where there is room for policy improvement.

To begin, import Building_Permits.csv from the Kaggle webpage.

corr = pd.crosstab(permits["Existing Use"], permits["Current Status"])

chi2, p, dof, expected = scipy.stats.chi2_contingency(corr)

# Computer Cramer's V
n = corr.sum().sum()
phi2 = chi2 / n
r, k = corr.shape
cramers_v = np.sqrt(phi2 / min(k-1, r-1))

print(f'Cramer\'s V: {cramers_v}')

Cramer's V: 0.04238999456003759

# Function to generate shades of a given color
def generate_shades(base_color, num_shades):
    base_color_rgb = np.array(mcolors.to_rgb(base_color))
    shades = [tuple(base_color_rgb * (1 - 0.5 * i / num_shades)) for i in range(num_shades)]
    return shades

The above graph isn't enough to determine a correlation. Let's test if there's a correlation between neighborhood and completion rate using a hypothesis test.

H0: Neighborhood doesn't affect the permit completion rate.

Ha: Neighborhood does affect the permit completion rate.

Print the p-value and determine if it's enough to reject the null hypothesis. Let alpha = 0.05.

In[]:
hypoth_data = pd.crosstab(permits_df["Completion Rate"], permits_df.index)

scipy.stats.chi2_contingency(hypoth_data).pvalue
Out[]:
0.2379043771131508

Since our p-value is above the alpha value, we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis, and therefore we fail to reject it. From this, we can conclude that the neighborhood a permit is in does not affect whether or not it is completed.

Primary Analysis & Developing the model

We want to determine how various independent factors we've cherry-picked in previous sections will impact the likelihood of a permit being approved. The neighborhood or existing use of land, for instance, could potentially impact the probability.

Because we are dealing with independent factors and trying to find a single probability, linear regression is a reasonable model. It tries to find a relationship between input factors and output a single numeric value based on the input values.

The independent factors that the model will be trained on are called features.

Many features are categorical, meaning they fall into discrete categories (as opposed to something like continuous numerical data), and the categories are strings.

Models might learn from the characters in these strings instead of the actual underlying data they're intended to represent. To address this issue, categorical data must be converted into discrete binary columns in a process called One-Hot Encoding.

If you've never learned about One-Hot Encoding before, check out this well-written article.

Use sklearn's OneHotEncoder to encode the categorical variables, which are all the features except the creation date, since time is continuous.

Why are zip codes categorical? While these numbers may be continuous, an increase or decrease in zip codes doesn't reveal anything about the neighborhood; a zip code is essentially a neighborhood described by a number, just like how neighboroods are described by strings/words in everyday life.

In[]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
import numpy as np
In[]:
encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False)

relevant_columns = ["Permit Type Definition", "Existing Use", "Neighborhoods", "Proposed Use"]

# Encode the data using fit_transform
encoded_columns = encoder.fit_transform(permits[relevant_columns])

permits = permits.drop(columns=relevant_columns) # Drop old categorical columns for one-hot encoding
permits = permits.drop(columns=["Current Status"])

encoded_df = pd.DataFrame(encoded_columns, columns=encoder.get_feature_names_out(relevant_columns))

permits = permits.reset_index(drop=True)
encoded_df = encoded_df.reset_index(drop=True)

permits = pd.concat([permits, encoded_df], axis=1) # Merge one-hot encoding with other data

permits.head() # To see the new data

Now that the categorical data is in a format that works better for machine learning models, we'll need to fix the "Permit Creation Date" column. Dates formatted as MM/DD/YYYY are strings, so like the categorical variables we just encoded, the machine learning model shouldn't be trained with this data.

Dates are not categorical thougha higher date (converted into a continous number like months or days) signifies a later point in time, and an increase or decrease in the number means something. However, day might be less relevant; based on how permits approvals work in the U.S., we can safely say the day relative to the start of a month is unlikely to really impact what happens to the permit.

Convert this column into a column of two integer columns, "Permit Creation Month" and "Permit Creation Year." Be sure to remove the original column once you're finished.

For help: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.Series.dt.year.html and https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.Series.dt.month.html

In[]:
# Convert the column into a datetime data format first
permits["Permit Creation Date"] = pd.to_datetime(permits['Permit Creation Date'], format='%m/%d/%Y')

permits["Permit Creation Month"] = permits["Permit Creation Date"].dt.month
permits["Permit Creation Year"] = permits["Permit Creation Date"].dt.year

permits = permits.drop(columns=["Permit Creation Date"])

Finally, the "Completed Date" column is important because it's the result of the independent variables. This is what needs to be classified. If the permit got completed, a date will exist, but otherwise it's NaN in the column.

Turn the NaN values into 0 and the values with dates into 1, and save that to a variable called Y, which will be the training labels.

Take everything else and save it to a variable called X, the training data input.

In[]:

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

In[]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=500, random_state=42, class_weight='balanced')
model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

# Evaluate the model using accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

accuracy
Out[]:
0.7541305580302907

This accuracy might be misleading. Oftentimes, machine learning models may perform well on specific test/train data splits, but not on others. K-Fold Validation creates different folds, each of which splits the data into different test/train groups, which can give a more holistic accuracy. Let's try K-Fold to double-check that our accuracy works as intended.

Confused? Check out this K-Fold Validation article: https://scikit-learn.org/1.5/modules/cross_validation.html

To implement this code sklearn's KFold: see https://scikit-learn.org/dev/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.KFold.html

In[]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold

model_fold = LogisticRegression(max_iter=500, random_state=42)

kfold = KFold(shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Step 4: Evaluate using cross_val_score
scores = cross_val_score(model_fold, X, y, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')

# Step 5: Print the results
scores

Finally, let's visualize the machine learning model's (the original one, anyway) confusion matrix. Confusion matrices give us information about a model's performance, including accuracy.

If you've never interacted with a confusion matrix before, check out a quick briefer: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/confusion-matrix-machine-learning/

In[]:
from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Create confusion matrix of True Positives, True Negatives, False Positives, and False Negatives
cfm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

# Use sklearn's ConfusionMatrixDisplay() function to create a visualization
cfm_display = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cfm, display_labels=['Completed', 'Not Completed'])

# Set colormap so green signifies a correct prediction and red signifies and incorrect prediction
cfm_display.plot(cmap=plt.cm.RdYlGn)

# Add title
cfm_display.ax_.set_title('Confusion Matrix')

plt.show()

Insights and Conclusions

The positive coefficients reveal some insights. Signs are likely to lead to a completed permit; a sensible outcome, as signs are quick to install and are unlikely to receive much of San Francisco's notorious NIMBY opposition.

Permits for single family homes, offices, retail spaces, and apartments are also likely to be completed. These are all common construction projects in big cities, and despite the housing shortage, it doesn't seem like housing is less likely to be constructed compared to other projects. In fact, the opposite is true! The San Francisco Standard reported that housing projects were completed in an increasing amount during the years represented in the dataset. So, housing is being completed, just not at the pace necessary to meet demand. Other factors like construction costs or tax policies might be discouraging permits from being submitted in the first place, which our data can't demonstrate.

From the negative coefficients we see that a missing Proposed Use in the permit severely impacts the completion status; this would make sense, as a permit that doesn't contain any informatin about its Proposed Use is unlikely to be approved and moved onto later stages.

What else? Note that land being used for automobile sales has a negative relationship with completion. San Francisco has been trending towards reduced car ownership for a while, but has struggled for many years to reduce the amount of space car-related infrastructure takes up. It would make sense that these automobile-related permits are less likely to reach a completed state as these may receive a lot of opposition from existing land owners or city residents unwilling to give up their cars.

The confusion matrix, and the accuracies from earlier, suggest that a good amount of test examples weren't classified correctly.

There could be many causes for this; most likely, it's possible that there isn't a strong relationship between many permit properties and the likelihood that the proposal will be completed. We saw earlier that completion rate was not impacted by neighborhoodthis is a huge factor in how housing gets constructed, as wealthier neighborhoods are known to oppose housing construction at higher rates.
